Then we keep in the action 4  the terms up to the second order
in the momenta  and in , integrate
over  and  and skip all derivative terms except
for the kinetic terms. We thus arrive at the matrix theory action
5.1 . Note that the form of the last term in 5.1  has
prompted us the dependence of the effective mass 4.1  on the
non-abelian fermions .



The Lorentz-covariant super-ND0-brane system  As it
has been considered in detail in the
ND-brane actions proposed in
 are not Lorentz
(or diffeomorphism) invariant in D-dimensional target space
except for the space filling branes. This is not because they are
constructed in the static gauge, which can be removed by restoring
the reparametrization invariance in the way discussed above. The
main reason is that the center-of-mass  coordinates 
of the ND-brane get mixed with the non-abelian  scalar
fields , which follows from the form of the action
3.1 . This implies that the motion of the center of mass of the
ND-brane as a whole depends on the internal excitations inside
the system, which is rather strange. One may wonder whether the
computation of string amplitudes associated with N coincident
D-branes of higher codimension confirms such an effect.

 We now consider the Lorentz-covariant counterpart of the above model.
 For this we assume the effective mass in () to be independent of the
spatial momenta . This ensures the free motion of the
ND0-brane center of mass. If so, we can now assume that the
indices  and  of ,  and
 are the indices of a corresponding representation of an
independet  internal group  which a priori  is
not related to the spatial subgroup of the Lorentz group
.

The supersymmetric and  invariant action for the Lorentz
invariant ND0-brane is
 
The variation properties of the fields with respect to the
symmetries of the action 36  are the same as written in
equations 5 -7 , 33 -psi , except that now the
spatial coordinates  transform in the standard way under the
-symmetry and target-space supersymmetry, i.e. there is
no contribution of the effective mass into their variation, and
the variation of  is Lorentz invariant.


Conclusion and discussion 
We have constructed the action for N coincident D0-branes which
is target-space supersymmtric and invariant under local worldline
fermionic -symmetry in a D-dimensional  superspace,
particular cases being  and type IIA . The action has
a generic structure determined by a super- and
-invariant effective mass which is a generic function of
the non-abelian  fields of the model and their momenta,
and which also depends on the spatial momentum of the center of
mass of the system. It is crucial for the invariance of the action
that the effective mass does not depend on  and
. In the bosonic limit the explicit form of the
effective mass is dictated by the non-abelian DBI structure of
the ND0-brane action, and it should still to be determined for
.

We have compared the supersymmetric ND0-brane action with that of
Matrix theory, which has allowed us to fix the dependence of the
effective mass 4.1  on the non-abelian  fermions
 up to the second order. A problem which remains is to
determine higher order fermionic terms in the effective mass.

It would be of interest to apply the T-duality procedure to the
supersymmetric ND0-brane model for getting supersymmetric actions
for higher dimensional coincident D-branes.

It would be also interesting to compare the above ND0-brane
construction with that of for the space filling
supersymmetric ND2-brane by performing the worldvolume
dimensional reduction of the latter.


